@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ----------------------------------------------------- To do -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Main" "To do"
@{U}2) To do@{UU}

   As I said before,  this is only  an beta version, so  there are still  some
things left to do, before I release the first full version 1.0 of Laplace, but
the countdown is constantly running down.

   If you have any @{B}suggestions@{UB}, you are invited to send me a note!!

   Here is a list of some major things:

 @{B}À@{UB} some smaller adjustments of the  plotter (function labels, font  adjust-
   ment).
 @{B}À@{UB} use integers of arbitary length
 @{B}À@{UB} export formulas and plotters as PS/EPS or bitmap file.
 @{B}À@{UB} complete and update documentation in english and german.
 @{B}À@{UB} a whole bunch of small improvementes...

   And here are some ideas for the @{I}beyond-V1.0 @{UI} future:

 @{B}À@{UB} 3D plotter, density-plots, vector-plots and other crazy things.
 @{B}À@{UB} symbolic integration (still a hard one, need some more time for it).
 @{B}À@{UB} port Laplace to other operating systems (X11, OS/2, Win95, BeOS...).


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ ® by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "KnownBugs"
@TITLE "Known bugs"
@NEXT "Competitors"
@PREV "ToDo"
@TOC "Manual.guide/Main"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ------------------------------------------------ Known bugs -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Main" "Known bugs"
@{U}3) Known bugs@{UU}

   If you find  a bug, not  documented feature etc.  don't hesitate, TELL  ME.
Laplace became a quite gigantic project  and consists now of about 55000  line
of program code. It is absolutely impossible to keep such an enormous  program
bug free. Another problem is that Laplace is quite difficult to debug. The GNU
debugger GDB would need about 25MB of free memory to load Laplace (I have 16MB
and VIRTUAL MEMORY  is terribly slow),  but the current  version doesn't  work
anyway (GDB is for some reason not  able to set breakpoints...). Instead of  a
source-level debugger, I have  to use MONAM, the  assembler debugger from  the
DEVPAC package...  did you  ever  see the  internal  representation of  a  C++
label...

   Here are those nasty things  I know, but didn't  manage to remove 'em  (for
now):

 @{B}À@{UB} The startup-window seems to be problematic  in some systems. If this  is
   the case on your configuration, it is possible to disable it completely.
   To do  this, you  have to  modify the  file @{B}Laplace@{UB},  which is  a  small
   shell-script. Load it to you favorite ASCII-editor and replace the  line
   @{B}bin/Laplace@{UB} by @{B}bin/Laplace -q@{UB}. If you start the installer-script in  ex-
   pert mode, this can be done by the installer-script.
 @{B}À@{UB} Rexx port is  currently not working,  and I don't  know, whether I  will
   reimplement it.
 @{B}À@{UB} There are still some  thing that look like  bugs, but are just  features
   that are not yet implemented. I was too lazy, to list them all (and per-
   haps even forgot them myself), so  don't hesitate to report things  that
   do not work as descripted in the manual.
 @{B}À@{UB} Asynchron calculation is still in an experimental state. Not all  struc-
   tures are protected for  simultaneous access by  different tasks, but  I
   didn't have any problems. I  have to check out,  if there could be  some
   conflicts.
 @{B}À@{UB} Laplace doesn't check for  out of memory conditions,  it assumes that  a
   memory allocation always succeeds. If an allocation fails, Laplace  sim-
   ply quits,  but this  leads to  a crash,  if the  allocation routine  is
   called from a sub task.


@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}------------------------------------------------------------------ ® by P!\K -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Competitors"
@TITLE "Competitors"
@NEXT "Biography"
@PREV "KnownBugs"
@TOC "Manual.guide/Main"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ----------------------------------------------- Competitors -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Main" "Competitors"
@{U}4) Competitors@{UU}

   There are many other math programs  for different operating systems, but  I
will only look at those available for AMIGA. Well most of them are quite  pro-
fessional projects, with lots of studied coders and mathematicians behind,  so
I cannot compete with them. But just have a look at them.

@{U}MAPLEV@{UU}

   Well, what to say about it? I didn't see the AMIGA version, but I know  the
UN*X version, and I think there are not many differences, at least I think the
mathematical functionality is the same.

   MAPLEV does almost everythink for you, you can think of. Integrals, differ-
ential equations, eigenvectors, function plotting etc. If there would not be a
small problem, I would  have never written Laplace:  the price. DM1500.- is  a
lot of money, which I cannot afford. This was probably the main reason to cre-
ate Laplace. Although there is a cheaper student version for AMIGA systems,  I
will continue my work, 'cause it's too much work to be wasted! If the price is
not a problem for you, don't hesitate to erase Laplace from your harddisk.

@{U}PARI@{UU}

   PARI is a freeware project of the university of Bordeaux, France. It lack a
graphical user interface,  but offers some  interesting features. The  biggest
advantage is:  it's really  fast! PARI's  best sides  are algebraic  calculus,
polynomials and power series. On the other  side, it is not able to  integrate
functions other than polynomials. For  transcendential functions a taylor  ex-
pansion will be  integrated, which is  at least a  good approximation, but  it
just gives up on broken rational  functions. It has a simple function  plotter
and basic online help, plus a 500k dvi-manual.

   PARI   is   available    on   AMINET,   it's    split   into   two    files
@{B}misc/math/gpamiga_1_38_3.lha@{UB} (binary)  and  @{B}misc/math/pari_1_38_3.lha@{UB}  (source
and  docs).   Versions  for   other   operating  system   can  be   found   at
@{B}megrez.ceremab.u-bordeaux.fr@{UB} (147.210.16.17) and @{B}math.ucla.edu@{UB} (FTP). You  can
contact the authors via e-mail at @{B}pari@ceremab.u-bordeaux.fr@{UB}.

@{U}MuPAD@{UU}

   MuPAD is also  free project of  the university of  Paderborn, Germany.  The
AMIGA version is still an alpha release and lacks a graphical user  interface.
It requires an FPU  (which I don't own),  so I wasn't able  to test it.  There
might be an UN*X version that I can test.

   All     files     related     to     MuPAD     can     be     found      at
@{B}math-ftp.uni-paderborn.de/pub/MuPAD/@{UB}                 (FTP)                 and
@{B}http://math-www.uni-paderborn.de/MuPAD/@{UB} (WWW).


