@NODE "Future"
@TITLE "Future plans"
@NEXT "README-MUI"
@PREV "Biography"
@TOC "Manual.guide/Main"
@{FG SHINE}@{BG SHADOW}@{B}- Laplace Manual ---------------------------------------------- Future plans -@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{UB}

@REM KEY 0 0 "Main" "Future plans"
@{U}6) Future plans@{UU}

   Two big questions are: @{I}Will I continue to develop Laplace? @{UI} and @{I}Will I con-@{UI}
@{I}tinue to support the AMIGA? @{UI}

   The answer to both questions is: @{I}Yes! @{UI}

   But I want to say something more about this topic. The future of the  AMIGA
look not too good - as you all know - and in my option there will probably not
be a serious chance for it. The AMIGA doesn't really have a chance again  Win-
Tel & Co., there will be some @{I}hardcore @{UI} AMIGA users for a long time (as  there
are C64 freaks today), but the scene is shrinking. On the long term the  AMIGA
will disappear.

   In former time I was  one of those @{I}hardcore @{UI}  AMIGA freaks, there could  be
only one: AMIGA! PC sucks, just because it's PC. But my philosophy changed,  I
don't think that the hardware or operating system is the most important thing,
and I would not support  a system out of some  dogmatic reasons. I'm a  coder,
what I need is a  developer environment and some  pieces of software. And  I'm
one of those old-style computer freaks: I  need a shell, I use makefiles,  TeX
and other things without a fancy GUI. Thereby I am quite happy with any system
that offers a UNIX like interface, including the AMIGA.

   One of the main  reasons for this change  of my point of  view is that  the
computer and software market develops much too fast to stick to a specific op-
erating system. If you develop  your software for a  specific OS, you have  to
rewrite the next year, because @{I}your @{UI} OS outdated. My point is that the  appli-
cation itself should be independent of the OS, instead you use some stub  rou-
tines that can easily be  adapted to the new system.  This way, you could  de-
velop your program on a nice UNIX  system, but you still have for example  the
big Windows market with lost of potential customers.

   For me this means that I will someday buy myself a nice PC and install some
nice Linux or whatever. Today I see  no reason, why I should abandon  Laplace,
which means that I will  continue the work on  another OS. I already  prepared
Laplace in a way that makes it as easy as possible to port it to another oper-
ating system. But this  does @{B}not@{UB} mean  that I will quit  the AMIGA version  of
Laplace and only publish versions for  other operating systems. If it is  easy
to port Laplace that was written on  an AMIGA to another operating system,  it
should be much easier to port it back to the AMIGA, if I continue the develop-
ment on another OS.

   As long as my good, old A1200 is working,  I will use it and I don't see  a
reason why I should today turn to a  PC. But everyone has to die, even a  com-
puter. And I don't  think that I  would buy another  AMIGA. But, don't  worry,
there is a fine thing called UAE -  the UNIX AMIGA EMULATOR. As far as I  know
it's quite good, and it  could work that I develop  Laplace on e.g. Linux  and
when I release a  new version, compile  it for the  AMIGA community using  the
UAE. Or - another possibility - I  find someone with a working AMIGA who  com-
piles it for me.

   And this means for you that you don't have to worry that you could register
to a program that won't be developed further. And if you think about buying  a
PC, too, you could use your AMIGA keyfile for a (still not written) PC version
of Laplace!


   But for the near future  (let's say the next year)  this is just much  talk
about nothing. As long as my AMIGA is not exploding right under my hands noth-
ing will change: I will write and write and write... today the development  of
Laplace is in fact my primary occupation.


